data.content:
## What breaks in .NET 11

**Sync I/O on the Cosmos DB provider is fully removed.** In .NET 10, you had the sync-over-async opt-in to allow `ToList()`, `First()`, `SaveChanges()`, etc. In EF Core 11, that opt-in no longer exists — **all synchronous I/O calls unconditionally throw at runtime**.

### Your code must become async:

```csharp
public class ProductRepository
{
    private readonly CosmosDbContext _context;

    public async Task<List<Product>> GetAllAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.ToListAsync();
    }

    public async Task<Product> GetByIdAsync(int id)
    {
        return await _context.Products.FirstAsync(p => p.Id == id);
    }

    public async Task<int> GetCountAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.CountAsync();
    }

    public async Task SaveAsync(Product product)
    {
        _context.Products.Add(product);
        await _context.SaveChangesAsync();
    }
}
```

**Key points:**
- There is **no workaround** — no opt-in, no config flag to restore sync behavior.
- This applies to all sync LINQ operators (`ToList`, `First`, `Single`, `Count`, `Any`) and `SaveChanges`.
- You'll also need to propagate `async/await` up through your callers (controllers, services, etc.).

Tracking issue: https://github.com/dotnet/efcore/issues/37059
